

<section xml:id="Ch3Sec1DefinitionsExamples">
  <title>Definitions and Examples</title>

  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>Define linear maps, a way of translating information between two vector spaces.</li>
      <li>Discuss many examples of linear maps.</li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

<subsection>
  <title>Definition of a linear map</title>
<!--
    <figure>
        <caption>Video recording for the intro to and definition of a linear map.</caption>
        <video source="https://learn.sun.ac.za/pluginfile.php/1653776/mod_folder/content/0/Lec16LinearMapIntroAndDefn.mp4" width="50%" preview="../latex/images/preview-doc-cam.jpg" onerror="this.src='Default.jpg'" />
    </figure>
-->
  <p>
    Recall that a <em>function</em>
    (or a <em>map</em>)
    <m>f : X \rightarrow Y</m> from a set <m>X</m> to a set <m>Y</m> is
    a rule which assigns to each element <m>x\in X</m> an element <m>f(x)</m> of <m>Y</m>.
    We write <m>x \mapsto f(x)</m> to indicate that an element <m>x \in X</m> maps to
    <m>f(x) \in Y</m> under the function <m>f</m>.
    See <xref ref="explanation_of_mapsto">Figure</xref>.
    Two functions <m>f, g : X \rightarrow Y</m> are <em>equal</em>
    if <m>f(x) = g(x)</m> for all <m>x</m> in <m>X</m>.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="explanation_of_mapsto">
    <caption>A function <m>f : X \rightarrow Y</m>.</caption>
    <image width="60%">
      <latex-image>
        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw (-2, 0) circle (1);
        \draw (2,0) circle (1);
        \node at (-2, -1.3) {\(X\)};
        \node at (2, -1.3) {\(Y\)};
        \draw[->] (-0.8, 0.3) to[out=30, in=150] node[above] {\(f\)} (0.8, 0.3);
        \node (a) at (-2, -0.5) {\(x\)};
        \node (b) at (2, -0.5) {\(f(x)\)};
        \draw[|->] (a) to[out=-20, in=200] (b);\end{tikzpicture}]]>
      </latex-image>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>V</m> and <m>W</m> be vector spaces.
        A <term>linear map</term>
        (also called a <term>linear transformation</term>)
        from <m>V</m> to <m>W</m> is a function <m>T : V \rightarrow W</m> satisfying:

        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>T(\ve{v} + \ve{v}') = T(\ve{v}) + T(\ve{v}')</m> for all vectors <m>\ve{v}, \ve{v}' \in V</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>T(k \ve{v}) = k T (\ve{v})</m> for all vectors
              <m>\ve{v} \in V</m> and all scalars <m>k \in \mathbb{R}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
    The case where <m>V=W</m> is exceptional enough that we give a special name for a linear map in that case.
  </p>

  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A linear map <m>T</m> from a vector space <m>V</m> to itself is called a <term>linear operator</term>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

</subsection>

<subsection>
  <title>Examples of linear maps</title>

  <example xml:id="matrices-give-rise-to-linear-maps-example">
    <title>Matrices give rise to linear maps</title>
    <statement>
<!--
      <figure>
        <caption>Video recording for <xref ref="matrices-give-rise-to-linear-maps-example"/>.</caption>
        <video source="https://learn.sun.ac.za/pluginfile.php/1653776/mod_folder/content/0/Lec16LinearMapDemo.mp4" width="70%" preview="../latex/images/preview-doc-cam.jpg" onerror="this.src='Default.jpg'" />
      </figure>
-->
      <p>
        Every <m>n \times m</m> matrix <m>\mat{A}</m> induces a <em>linear map</em>
        <md>
          <mrow>T_{\mat{A}} : \Col_m \amp  \rightarrow \Col_n</mrow>
          <mrow>\col{v} \amp  \mapsto \mat{A} \col{v} \, </mrow>
        </md>.
      </p>

      <p>
        That is, <m>T_{\mat{A}} (\col{v}) := \mat{A} \col{v}</m> is the matrix product of <m>\mat{A}</m> with the column vector <m>\col{v}</m>.
        The fact that <m>T_\mat{A}</m> is indeed a linear map follows from the linearity of matrix multiplication
        (<xref ref="props_of_matrix_ops">Proposition</xref> parts 2 and 3).
      </p>

      <p>
        Note that an <m>n \times m</m> matrix gives rise to a linear map from <m>\Col_m</m> to <m>\Col_n</m>!
      </p>

      <p>
        For instance, consider
        <me>
          A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix}
        </me>
        This gives rise to a linear map
        <md>
         <mrow> T : \Col_2 \amp \rightarrow \Col_2 </mrow>
         <mrow> \begin{bmatrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \end{bmatrix} \amp \mapsto \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
        </md>
        The following interactive Geogebra app demonstrates this. Drag the red vector <m>\col{v}</m> around to see the effect on <m>\mat{A} \col{v}</m>. You can also change the coefficients of the matrix <m>\mat{A}</m> by dragging the sliders.
      </p>
      <figure>
        <title>Geogebra app</title>
        <caption>  Interactive GeoGebra applet displaying the linear map <m>\col{v} \mapsto \mat{A}\col{v}</m>.</caption>
        <interactive geogebra="https://www.geogebra.org/material/iframe/id/vexfrzez/width/600/height/701/border/888888/sfsb/true/smb/false/stb/false/stbh/false/ai/false/asb/false/sri/false/rc/false/ld/false/sdz/false/ctl/false" aspect="600:701" width="90%" preview="../../images/interactive-preview-3.png"/>
      </figure>
    </statement>
  </example>

<example>
<title>A non-linear map</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      The following interactive JSXGraph applet illustrates the <q>polar coordinates</q> map
      <md>
        <mrow> T : \mathbb{R}^2 \amp \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^2 </mrow>
        <mrow> \begin{bmatrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \end{bmatrix} \amp \mapsto \begin{bmatrix} v_1 \cos(\pi v_2) \\ v_1 \sin(\pi v_2)  \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
      </md>
      Note that <m>T</m> is a non-linear map, since, for most points <m>\ve{v}, \ve{v}' \in \mathbb{R}^2</m>, we have <m>T(\ve{v} + \ve{v}') \neq T(\ve{v}) + T(\ve{v}')</m>.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <caption>Polar coordinates as a non-linear map.</caption>
      <interactive xml:id="interactive-polar-map" platform="jsxgraph" source="code/jsxgraph/PolarCoordMap.js" aspect="10:4" preview="../../images/interactive-polar-map-preview.png">
        <sidebyside widths="40% 5% 40%" valign="middle">
          <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-polar-1" surface="jsxboard"/>
          <p><m> \xrightarrow{ \large T } </m></p>
          <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-polar-2" surface="jsxboard"/>
        </sidebyside>
        <instructions>
            <p>Drag the point <m>\ve{v}</m> to see the effect on <m>T(\ve{v})</m>.</p>
        </instructions>
      </interactive>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Another way to see that <m>T</m> is non-linear is that <m>T</m> does not send straight lines to straight lines.
    </p>
  </statement>
</example>

  <example>
    <title>Identity map</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>V</m> be a vector space.
        The function
        <md>
          <mrow>\id_V : V \amp \rightarrow V</mrow>
          <mrow>\ve{v} \amp  \mapsto \ve{v}</mrow>
        </md>
        is called the <em>identity map</em> on <m>V</m>.
        It is clearly a linear map, since
        <md>
          <mrow>\id_V (\ve{v} + \ve{w}) \amp = \ve{v} + \ve{w}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \id_V (\ve{v}) + \id_V (\ve{w})</mrow>
        </md>
        and
        <md>
          <mrow>\id_V (k \ve{v}) \amp = k \ve{v}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = k \id_V (\ve{v})</mrow>
        </md>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="projection_map_example">
    <title>Projection as a linear map</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
      The function
      <md>
        <mrow>T : \mathbb{R}^2 \amp \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</mrow>
        <mrow>(x, y) \amp \mapsto x</mrow>
      </md>
      which projects vectors onto the <m>x</m>-axis is a linear map.
    </p>

    <p>
      Let us check additivity algebraically:
      <me>
        T \left ( (x_1, y_1 ) + (x_2, y_2) \right) \stackrel{\text{?} }{=} T\left((x_1, y_1) \right) + T\left((x_2, y_2)\right)
      </me>
      <md>
        <mrow>\text{LHS}  \amp = T \left( (x_1 + x_2, y_1 + y_2) \right) \amp  \text{RHS}  \amp = x_1 + x_2</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = x_1 + x_2</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      Here is a a graphical version of this proof:
    </p>

    <figure>
      <caption>
      </caption>
      <image width="70%">
        <latex-image>
          <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}[xscale=1.5]
          \draw[<->] (-1, 0) -- (3, 0);
          \draw[<->] (0, -1) -- (0, 3);
          \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0,0) -- node[above left] {\(\ve{v}\)} (0.5, 1) ;
          \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0.5,1) -- node[above left] {\(\ve{w}\)} (1.5, 1.5) ;
          \draw[dotted] (0.5, 1) -- (0.5, 0);
          \draw[dotted] (1.5, 1.5) -- (1.5, 0);
          \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0,0) -- node[below] {\(T(\ve{v})\)} (0.5, 0) ;
          \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0.5, 0) -- node[below] {\(T(\ve{w})\)} (1.5, 0) ;
          \node[primaryColor] at (2.3, 0.3) {\(T(\ve{v} + \ve{w})\)};
          \node[primaryColor] at (2.3, -0.3) {\(T(\ve{v}) + T(\ve{w})\)};\end{tikzpicture}]]>
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove algebraically that we also have <m>T(k \ve{v}) = k T(\ve{v})</m>,
        so that <m>T</m> is a linear map.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        We only need to do the following computation:
        <me> T(k \ve v) = T(k(x,y)) = T(kx,ky) = kx = kT((x,y)) = kT(\ve v)  </me>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <example xml:id="rotation_as_linear_map">
    <title>Rotation as a linear map</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Fix an angle <m>\theta</m>.
        The function
        <md>
          <mrow>R_\theta : \mathbb{R}^2 \amp  \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^2</mrow>
          <mrow>\ve{v} \amp  \mapsto \text{rotation of } \ve{v} \text{ counterclockwise through angle }\theta</mrow>
        </md>
        is a linear map,
        by a similar graphical argument as in <xref ref="projection_map_example">Example</xref>.
      </p>

      <figure>
        <caption>
        </caption>
        <image width="40%">
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw[<->] (-1, 0) -- (2, 0);
            \draw[<->] (0, -1) -- (0, 2);
            \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0,0) -- (30:1.5) node[right] {\(\ve{v}\)} ;
            \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0,0) --  (70:1.5) node[above] {\(R (\ve{v})\)};
            \draw (30:0.5) arc (30:70:0.5) node[xshift=2pt, yshift=2pt, right] {\(\theta\)} ;\end{tikzpicture}]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

    </statement>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="cross_prod_as_linear_map">
    <title>Cross product with a fixed vector as a linear map</title>
    <statement>
<!--
    <figure>
        <caption>Video recording for <xref ref="cross_prod_as_linear_map"/>.</caption>
        <video source="https://learn.sun.ac.za/pluginfile.php/1653776/mod_folder/content/0/Lec16CrossProduct.mp4" width="70%" preview="../latex/images/preview-doc-cam.jpg" onerror="this.src='Default.jpg'" />
    </figure>
-->
      <p>
        Fix a vector <m>\ve{w} \in \mathbb{R}^3</m>.
        The function
        <md>
          <mrow>C : \mathbb{R}^3 \amp \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^3</mrow>
          <mrow>\ve{v} \amp  \mapsto \ve{w} \times \ve{v}</mrow>
        </md>
        is a linear map because of the properties of the cross-product,
        <md>
          <mrow>\ve{w} \times (\ve{v}_1 + \ve{v}_2) \amp = \ve{w} \times \ve{v}_1 + \ve{w} \times \ve{v}_2</mrow>
          <mrow>\ve{w} \times (k \ve{v}) \amp = k \ve{w} \times \ve{v}</mrow>
        </md>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="dot_prod_with_fix_vec">
    <title>Dot product with a fixed vector as a linear map</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Fix a vector <m>\ve{u} \in \mathbb{R}^3</m>.
        The function
        <md>
          <mrow>D : \mathbb{R}^3 \amp \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</mrow>
          <mrow>\ve{v} \amp  \mapsto \ve{u} \dotp \ve{v}</mrow>
        </md>
        (here <m>\cdot</m> is the dot product of vectors,
        not scalar multiplication!) is a linear map, because of the properties
        <md>
          <mrow>\ve{u} \dotp (\ve{v}_1 + \ve{v}_2) \amp = \ve{u} \dotp \ve{v}_1 + \ve{u} \smul\ve{v}_2</mrow>
          <mrow>\ve{u} \smul(k \ve{v}) \amp = k \ve{u} \dotp \ve{v}</mrow>
        </md>.
      </p>

        <p>
          We will soon see that <em>all</em>
          linear maps <m>\mathbb{R}^3 \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m>
          (indeed all linear maps <m>\mathbb{R}^n \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m>)
          are of this form.
        </p>

    </statement>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="diff_of_poly">
    <title>Differentiation as a linear map</title>
    <statement>
<!--
    <figure>
        <caption>Video recording for <xref ref="diff_of_poly"/>.</caption>
        <video source="https://learn.sun.ac.za/pluginfile.php/1653776/mod_folder/content/0/Lec16Differentiation.mp4" width="70%" preview="../latex/images/preview-doc-cam.jpg" onerror="this.src='Default.jpg'" />
    </figure>
-->
    <p>
      The operation <q>take the derivative</q> can be interpreted as a linear map
      <md>
        <mrow>D : \Poly_n \amp  \rightarrow \Poly_{n-1}</mrow>
        <mrow>p \amp  \mapsto p' \, </mrow>
      </md>.
      For example, <m>D(2x^3 - 6x + 2) = 6x^2 - 6</m>.
    </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <ol label="(a)">
        <li><p> Why is <m>D</m> a map from <m>\Poly_n</m> to <m>\Poly_{n-1}</m>?</p></li>
        <li><p> Check that <m>D</m> is linear.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              As you know from calculus, taking the derivative of a polynomial decreases every power of <m> x </m> by 1. So if <m> p </m> is in <m>\Poly_n </m>, then <m> p </m> has degree at most <m> n </m> . Therefore, its image under <m> D </m> has degree at most <m> n - 1</m>. Thus <m> p' </m> is in <m>\Poly_{n-1} </m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m> p, q </m> be in <m> \Poly_n </m>. Then:
              <md>
                <mrow>
                  D(p + q) \amp = (p+q)'
                </mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = p' + q' \amp (\text{rule of differentiation})</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = D(p) + D(q) </mrow>
              </md>
            </p>
            <p>
              Similarly,
              <md>
                <mrow> D(kp) \amp = (kp)' </mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = kp' \amp (\text{rule of differentiation})</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = k D(p)</mrow>
              </md>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <example xml:id="antiderivative-as-linear-map-example">
    <title>Antiderivative as a linear map</title>
    <statement>
<!--
      <figure>
        <caption>Video recording for <xref ref="antiderivative-as-linear-map-example"/>.</caption>
        <video source="https://learn.sun.ac.za/pluginfile.php/1653776/mod_folder/content/0/Lec16Antiderivative.mp4" width="70%" preview="../latex/images/preview-doc-cam.jpg" onerror="this.src='Default.jpg'" />
      </figure>
-->
    <p>
      The operation <q>find the unique anti-derivative with zero constant term</q> can be interpreted as a linear map
      <md>
        <mrow>A : \Poly_n \amp  \rightarrow \Poly_{n+1}</mrow>
        <mrow>\ve{p} \amp  \mapsto \int_0^x \ve{p}(t) \, dt</mrow>
      </md>
      For example, <m>A(2x^3 - 6x + 2) = 4 x^4 - 3x^2 + 2x</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  </example>

  <exercise>
      <statement>
        <ol label="(a)">
          <li><p>
            Why is <m>A</m> a map from <m>\Poly_n</m> to <m>\Poly_{n+1}</m>?
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            Check that <m>A</m> is indeed a linear map.
          </p></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol label="(a)">
            <li>
              <p>
              You know from calculus that the antiderivative of a polynomial <m> \ve p </m> must always have degree one greater than <m> \ve p </m>. Hence <m> A </m> maps <m>\Poly_n</m> to <m> \Poly_{n+1}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m> \ve p , \ve q </m> be in <m> \Poly_n </m>. Using the usual properties of the integral, we compute
                <md>
                  <mrow>
                  A(\ve p + \ve q) \amp = \int_0^x \ve p(t) + \ve q(t) \, dt = \int_0^x \ve p(t) \, dt + \int_0^x \ve q(t) \, dt </mrow>
                  <mrow> \amp = A(\ve p) + A(\ve q)</mrow>
                </md>.
                Similarly,
                <me>
                  A (k\ve p) = k\int_0^x \ve p(t) \, dt = \int_0^x k\ve p(t) \, dt = A(k\ve p).
                </me>
                </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

  <example xml:id="shift_example">
    <title>Shift map</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
      Define the <q>shift forward by 1</q> map
      <md>
        <mrow>S : \Poly_n \amp  \rightarrow \Poly_n</mrow>
        <mrow>\ve{p} \amp  \mapsto S( \ve{p})</mrow>
      </md>
      by <m>S(\ve{p})(x) = \ve{p}(x-1)</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Consider the case <m>n=3</m>.
      In terms of the standard basis
      <me>
        \ve{p}_0 (x) = 1, \, \ve{p}_1 (x) = x, \, \ve{p}_2 (x) = x^2, \, \ve{p}_3 (x) = x^3
      </me>
      of <m>\Poly_3</m>, we have:
      <md>
        <mrow>S(\ve{p}_0) \amp = \ve{p}_0</mrow>
        <mrow>S(\ve{p}_1) \amp = \ve{p}_1 - \ve{p}_0</mrow>
        <mrow>S(\ve{p}_2) \amp = \ve{p}_2 - 2 \ve{p}_1 + \ve{p}_0</mrow>
        <mrow>S(\ve{p}_3) \amp = \ve{p}_3 - 3 \ve{p}_2 + 3 \ve{p}_1 - \ve{p}_0</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Check that <m>S</m> is a linear map.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Let
          <md>
            <mrow>
            \ve p \amp = \sum_{j=0}^n a_j x^j \amp
            \ve q \amp= \sum_{j=0}^n b_j x^j
            </mrow>
          </md>
          We have to check
          <me>
            S(k \ve p ) = S\left( \sum_{j=0}^n ka_j x^j\right) = \sum_{j=0}^n ka_j (x-1)^j =  k \sum_{j=0}^n a_j (x-1)^j = kS(\ve p)
          </me>
          and
          <md>
            <mrow> S(\ve p + \ve q) \amp = S\left(\sum_{j=0}^n (a_j + b_j) x^j\right) = \sum_{j=0}^n (a_j + b_j) (x-1)^j </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \sum_{j=0}^n a_j (x-1)^j + \sum_{j=0}^n  b_j (x-1)^j = S(\ve p) + S(\ve q)</mrow>
          </md>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Check the formulas for <m>S(\ve{p}_0), S(\ve{p}_1), S(\ve{p}_2), S(\ve{p}_3),</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m> S(\ve p_0) = \ve p_0 </m> is trivial.
          Then we have
          <md>
            <mrow> S(\ve p_1) \amp = x-1 = \ve p_1 - \ve p_0 </mrow>
            <mrow> S(\ve p_2) \amp = (x-1)^2 = x^2 - 2x + 1 = \ve p_2 - 2\ve p_1 + \ve p_0 </mrow>
            <mrow>S(\ve p_3) \amp = (x-1)^3 = x^3 - 3x^2 + 3x - 1 = \ve{p}_3 - 3 \ve{p}_2 + 3 \ve{p}_1 - \ve{p}_0</mrow>
          </md>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

  <example xml:id="grad_as_linear_map">
    <title>Gradient as a linear map</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Recall the vector space <m>\Poly_n</m> of polynomials in <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> (<xref ref="poly_many_variables_example"/>, dimension computed in <xref ref="dim_poly_many_variables"/>) and the vector space <m>\Vect_n (\mathbb{R}^2)</m> of polynomial vector fields on <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> (<xref ref="poly_vector_fields_example"/>, dimension computed in <xref ref="dim_poly_vec_fields"/>).
      </p>

      <p>
        The operation <q>take the gradient</q> can be thought of as a linear map
        <md>
          <mrow> \nabla : \Poly_n[x,y] \amp \rightarrow \Vect_{n-1} (\mathbb{R}^2) </mrow>
          <mrow> f \amp \mapsto \nabla f </mrow>
        </md>
        This is a linear map because <m>\nabla(f + g) = \nabla f + \nabla g </m> and <m>\nabla (kf) = k \nabla f</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        For example,
        <me>
          \nabla(x + xy) = (1 + y, x).
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <example>
  <title>Double integral as a linear map</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>D \subseteq \mathbb{R}^2</m> be a region in the plane. Integrating polynomial functions over <m>D</m> can be thought of as a linear map
      <md>
        <mrow> I : \Poly_n [x,y] \amp \mapsto \mathbb{R} </mrow>
        <mrow> f \amp \mapsto \iint_{D} f dA </mrow>
      </md>
      This is a linear map because
      <md>
        <mrow> \iint_D (f+g) dA \amp = \iint_D f dA + \iint_D g dA </mrow>
        <mrow> \iint_D kf \, dA \amp = k \iint_D f \, dA </mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      For example, let <m>D = \{ (x,y) : x^2 + y^2 \leq 1 \} </m>, and let <m>f = x^2</m>. Then
      <me>
        I(f) = \iint_D x^2 \, dA = \frac{\pi}{4}
      </me>
      as the reader will verify.
    </p>
   </statement>
  </example>

<example xml:id="initial_conditions_as_linear_map">
  <title>Initial conditions for differential equations as a linear map</title>
  <statement>
  <p>
    Let <m>V</m> be the vector space of solutions to a 2nd order linear homogenous ordinary differential equation on an interval <m>I</m>:
    <me>
      y^{''} + a_1(x) y'+ a_0(x) y = 0, \quad x \in I.
    </me>
    Fix a point <m>x_0 \in I</m>. Then we get a linear map
    <md>
      <mrow> T_{x_0} : \Col_2 \amp \rightarrow V </mrow>
      <mrow> \begin{bmatrix} a \\ b \end{bmatrix} \amp \mapsto \text{unique } y \in V \text{ such that } y(x_0) = a, y'(x_0)=b </mrow>
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>(Now is a good time to review <xref ref="diff_eqn_exist_unique"/> and <xref ref="geogebra_diff_eqn_1"/>.) </p>

  <p>
    This is illustrated in <xref ref="ode_lin_map"/> for the case of the differential equation
    <me>
       y^{''}  + xy = 0.
    </me>
    Drag the blue vector <m>\ve{v}</m> to see the effect on its image <m>T_{x_0}(\ve{v}) = y</m> in <m>V</m>. You can also change the value of <m>x_0</m>.
  </p>
    <figure xml:id="ode_lin_map">
      <interactive geogebra="https://www.geogebra.org/material/iframe/id/kxcmtv5t/width/800/height/909/border/888888/sfsb/true/smb/false/stb/false/stbh/false/ai/false/asb/false/sri/false/rc/false/ld/false/sdz/false/ctl/false" aspect="800:909" width="90%" preview="../../images/interactive-preview-5.png"/>
      <caption>GeoGebra App: Understanding the linear map <m>T</m>.</caption>
    </figure>
</statement>
</example>

</subsection>

<subsection>
  <title>Some results about linear maps</title>

  <lemma xml:id="lin_map_zero_to_zero">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>T : V \rightarrow W</m> is a linear map.
        Then

        <ol label="(a)">
          <li xml:id="lin_map_zero_to_zero_1">
            <p>
              <m>T(\ve{0}_V) = \ve{0}_W</m>;
            </p>
          </li>

          <li xml:id="lin_map_zero_to_zero_2">
            <p>
              <m>T(-\ve{v}) = - T(\ve{v})</m> for all vectors <m>\ve{v} \in V</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </lemma>

  <proof>
    <p>
      We leave (<xref ref="lin_map_zero_to_zero_1" text="local" />) as <xref ref="exercise-zero-maps-to-zero" /> and go to work as follows for (<xref ref="lin_map_zero_to_zero_2" text="local" />):
      <md>
        <mrow> T(-\ve{v}) \amp = T( (-1) \ve{v}) \amp  \text{(defn of } -\ve{v} \text{ in } V)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = (-1) T(\ve{v}) \amp  (T \text{ is linear)}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = - T(\ve{v}) \amp  \text{(defn of }-T(\ve{v}) \text{ in } W)</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
  </proof>

  <p>
    The next result is very important.
    It tells us that if we know how a linear map <m>T</m> acts on a basis,
    then we know how it acts on the whole vector space
    (this is the <q>uniqueness</q> part).
    Moreover, we are free to write down any willy-nilly formula for what <m>T</m> does on the basis vectors,
    and we are guaranteed that this will always extend to a linear map defined on the whole vector space
    (this is the <q>existence</q> part).
  </p>

  <proposition xml:id="defining_linear_map_on_basis">
    <title>Sufficient to define a linear map on a basis</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>\basis{B} = \bopen \ve{e}_1, \ldots, \ve{e}_m \bclose</m> is a basis for <m>V</m> and
        <m>\ve{w}_1, \ldots, \ve{w}_m</m> are vectors in <m>W</m>.
        Then there exists a unique linear map <m>T : V \rightarrow W</m> such that
        <me>
          T(\ve{e}_i) = \ve{w}_i,  i = 1 \ldots m
        </me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </proposition>

  <proof>
    <p>
      First we show the <em>existence</em> of such a linear map.
      To define a linear map <m>T</m>,
      we must define <m>T(\ve{v})</m> for each vector <m>\ve{v}</m>.
      We can write any <m>\ve{v}</m> uniquely as a linear combination of the vectors in the basis <m>\basis{B}</m>:
      <men xml:id="expansion_of_v_in_coords">
        \ve{v} = a_1 \ve{e}_1 + \cdots + a_m \ve{e}_m
      </men>.
      We define
      <men xml:id="formula_for_T">
        T(\ve{v}) := a_1 \ve{w}_1 + a_2 \ve{w}_2 + \cdots a_m \ve{w}_m
      </men>.
    </p>

    <p>
      We clearly have <m>T(\ve{e}_i) = \ve{w}_i</m>.
      To complete the proof of existence,
      we must show that <m>T</m> is linear.
      For that, also let <m>\ve{v}' = b_1\ve{e}_1+\cdots+b_m\ve{e}_m</m>. Then
      <md>
        <mrow>T(\ve{v} + \ve{v}') \amp = (a_1 + b_1) \ve{w}_1 + \cdots + (a_m + b_m) \ve{w}_m</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp =  \big(a_1 \ve{w}_1 + \cdots + a_m \ve{w}_m \big)  + \big(b_1 \ve{w}_1 + \cdots + b_m \ve{w}_m \big)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = T(\ve{v}) + T(\ve{w})</mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Similarly, one can check that <m>T(k \ve{v}) = k T(\ve{v})</m>,
      which completes the proof of existence.
    </p>

    <p>
      Now we prove the <em>uniqueness</em> of such a linear map.
      Suppose that <m>S, T  : V \rightarrow W</m> are linear maps with
      <men xml:id="thing_to_satisfy">
        S(\ve{e}_i) = \ve{w}_i,  \text{ and }   T(\ve{e}_i) = \ve{w}_i,  i = 1 \ldots m
      </men>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Then,
      <md>
        <mrow>S (\ve{v}) \amp = S\big(a_1 \ve{e}_1 + \cdots + a_m \ve{e}_m\big)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = a_1 S(\ve{e}_1) + \cdots + a_m S(\ve{e}_m) \amp (S \text{ is lineêr)}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = a_1 \ve{w}_1 + \cdots + a_m \ve{w}_m \amp  \text{(want } S(\ve{e}_i) = \ve{w}_i)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = a_1 T(\ve{e}_1) + \cdots + a_m T(\ve{e}_m) \amp  \text{(want } T(\ve{e}_i) = \ve{w}_i)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = T(a_1 \ve{e}_1 +  \cdots + a_m \ve{e}_m) \amp  (T \text{ is lineêr)}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = T(\ve{v})</mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Hence <m>S = T</m>,
      in other words the linear map satisfying <xref ref="thing_to_satisfy" /> is unique.
    </p>
  </proof>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        As an application of <xref ref="defining_linear_map_on_basis">Proposition</xref>,
        we can define a linear map
        <md>
          <mrow>T : \Col_2 \amp  \rightarrow \Fun(\mathbb{R})</mrow>
          <intertext>simply by defining its action on the standard basis of <m>\Col_2</m>. For instance, we may set</intertext>
          <mrow>\mat{e}_1 \amp  \rightarrow f_1</mrow>
          <mrow>\mat{e}_2 \amp  \rightarrow f_2</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        The point is that we are free to send <m>\mat{e}_1</m> and
        <m>\mat{e}_2</m> to <em>any functions</em>
        <m>f_1</m> and <m>f_2</m> we like,
        and we are assured that this will give a well-defined linear map <m>T : \Col_2 \rightarrow \Fun(\mathbb{R})</m>.
        For instance, we might set
        <m>f_1 (x) = \sin x</m> and <m>f_2 (x) = |x|</m>.
        Then the general formula for <m>T</m> is
        <me>
          \left(T \begin{bmatrix} a \\ b \end{bmatrix}\right)(x) = a \sin x + b |x|
        </me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="rotation-map-example-complete">
    <title>Rotation map on standard basis</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let us compute the action of the <q>counterclockwise rotation by <m>\theta</m></q> map <m>R</m> from <xref ref="rotation_as_linear_map">Example</xref>
        with respect to the standard basis <m>\ve{e}_1, \ve{e}_2</m> of <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>.
      </p>
      <sidebyside>
        <image width="40%">
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw[<->] (-1, 0) -- (2, 0);
            \draw[<->] (0, -1) -- (0, 2);
            \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0, 0) -- (1.5, 0) node[below left] {$\ve{e}_1$};
            \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0,0) -- (30:1.5) node[right] {$R(\ve{e}_1)$};
            \draw (0:0.5) arc (0:30:0.5) node[above] {$\theta$};\end{tikzpicture}]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
        <image width="40%">
          <latex-image>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw[<->] (-1, 0) -- (2, 0);
          \draw[<->] (0, -1) -- (0, 2);
          \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0, 0) -- (0, 1.5) node[right] {$\ve{e}_2$};
          \draw[very thick, primaryColor, ->] (0,0) -- (120:1.5) node[above] {$R(\ve{e}_2)$};
          \draw (90:0.5) arc (90:120:0.5) node[above, xshift=2pt, yshift=2pt] {$\theta$} ;\end{tikzpicture}]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>

      <p>
        From the figure, we have:
        <md>
          <mrow>R(\ve{e}_1) \amp = (\cos \theta, \sin \theta) \amp  R(\ve{e}_2) \amp = (-\sin \theta, \cos \theta)</mrow>
        </md>
        so that
        <md>
          <mrow>R(\ve{e}_1) \amp =  \cos \theta \, \ve{e}_1 + \sin \theta\, \ve{e}_2,  R(\ve{e}_2) = -\sin \theta \, \ve{e}_1 +  \cos \theta\, \ve{e}_2</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        Now that we know the action of <m>R</m> on the standard basis vectors,
        we can compute its action on an arbitrary vector <m>(x, y) \in \mathbb{R}^2</m>:
        <md>
          <mrow>R\left( (x,y)\right) \amp = R( x \ve{e}_1 + y \ve{e}_2 )</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = x R(\ve{e}_1) + y R(\ve{e}_2)</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = x (\cos \theta, \sin \theta) + y (-\sin \theta, \cos \theta)</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = (x \cos \theta - y \sin \theta, \, x \sin \theta + y \cos \theta)</mrow>
        </md>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

</subsection>

<exercises>
 <exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Determine whether the following are linear maps and motivate your answer:
    <ol label="(a)">
      <li>
        <m>T:\Row_3\to \Row_2</m> defined by <m>T(x,y,z) = (2x-y,x+y-z)</m>;
      </li>
      <li>
        <m>T:\Fun(\reals,\reals)\to \Row_2</m> defined by <m>T(f) = (f(1),f(0))</m>. (In other words, the input is a function from reals to reals and the output is the vector consisting of the values of <m>f</m> at 0 and 1.)
      </li>
      <li>
        <m>T:\Row_2\to \Row_2</m> defined by <m>T(x,y) = (x+1, y-2)</m>;
      </li>
      <li>
        <m>T:\Poly_2\to \Poly_3</m> defined by <m>T(p(x)) = xp(x)</m>. (I.e. the input polynomial gets multiplied by <m>x</m> and the result is the output.)
      </li>
      <li>
        <m>T:\Poly_2\to \Poly_4</m> defined by <m>T(p(x)) = (p(x))^2</m>;
      </li>
      <li>
        <m>T:\Poly_2\to \Poly_4</m> defined by <m>T(p(x)) = p(x^2)</m>. (What is the difference between this and the previous question?)
      </li>
      <li>
        <m>T:Func(\reals,\reals)\to Func(\reals,\reals)</m> defined by <m>T(f(x)) = f(x-1)</m>;
      </li>
      <li>
        <m>T:\Mat_{22}\to \reals</m> defined by <m>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} a\amp b\\c\amp d\end{bmatrix}\right) = ad-bc</m>.
      </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <answer>
    <p>
      (a), (b), (d), (f), (g) are linear; the others are not.
    </p>
  </answer>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <ol label="(a)">
        <li>
          Suppose that <m>\ve v_1 = (x_1,y_1,z_1)</m> en <m>\ve v_2 = (x_2,y_2,z_2)</m> are two vectors in <m>\Row_3</m>.
          Then
          <md>
            <mrow> T(x_1,y_1,z_1) \amp = (2x_1-y_1,x_1+y_1-z_1)</mrow>
            <mrow>T(x_2,y_2,z_2) \amp = (2x_2-y_2,x_2+y_2-z_2)</mrow>
            <mrow>T(x_1+x_2,y_1+y_2,z_1+z_2) \amp = (2(x_1+x_2)-(y_1+y_2),(x_1+x_2)+(y_1+y_2)-(z_1+z_2))</mrow>
          </md>
          and thus
          <me> T(\ve v_1+\ve v_2) = T(\ve v_1) + T(\ve v_2)</me>.
          Similarly, we show that
          <md>
            <mrow> T(c(x,y,z)) = T((cx,cy,cz)) = (2cx-cy,cx+cy-cz) = c(x-y,x+y-z) = cT((x,y,z))</mrow>
          </md>,
          so that <m>T(c\ve v) = cT(\ve v)</m> for all vectors <m>\ve v</m> and all scalars <m>c</m>.
          Since both conditions hold, <m>T</m> is linear.
        </li>
        <li>
          Let <m>f,g</m> be two arbitrary functions in <m>\Fun(\reals,\reals)</m>.
          Then we define <m>(f+g)</m> as the function that satisfies for each <m>x</m> that
          <me> (f+g)(x) := f(x) + g(x)</me>.
          In particular, we have
          <md><mrow> (f+g)(0) = f(0)+g(0) \amp\amp (f+g)(1) = f(1)+g(1)</mrow></md>.
          Thus
          <md>
            <mrow> T(f+g) \amp = ((f+g)(0),(f+g)(1)) = (f(0)+g(0),f(1)+g(1))</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = (f(0),g(0))+(f(1),g(1)) = T(f) + T(g)</mrow>
          </md>.
          Furthermore, the scalar product <m>cf</m> is defined as the function that satisfies for each  <m>x</m> that
          <me> (cf)(x) := c(f(x))</me>.
          Now we check
          <me> T(cf) = ((cf)(0),(cf)(1)) = (c(f(0)),c(f(1))) = c(f(0),f(1))=c(T(f))</me>.
          Thus <m>T</m> is linear.
        </li>
        <li>
          To prove that <m>T</m> is linear, we have to prove a general statement for all paris of vectors.
          But to show that it is not linear, we only need to find one pair of vectors for which one of the conditions doesn't hold.
          (Remember that if a condition <em>doesn't hold</em> for one particular value, then it <em>doesn't hold for all values</em> <mdash /> this is not the same as saying that for all values it doesn't hold!)
          We check that
          <me> T(0(0,0)) = T((0,0)) = (0+1,0-2) = (1,-2)</me>,
          while
          <me> 0(T(0,0)) = 0(1,-2) = (0,0)</me>.
          These two vectors are not equal, so <m>T</m> is not linear.
          Instead of this example of where the scalar product condition we could have given an example of where the sum condition fails. Or we could even just have noticed that the zero vector isn't mapped to the zero vector!
        </li>
        <li>
          We have
          <me>T(p+q) = x(p+q) = xp+xq = T(p)+T(q)</me>
          and
          <me> T(cp) = x(cp) = c(xp) = cT(p)</me>
          so <m>T</m> is linear.
        </li>
        <li>
          We give a counterexample:
          <me> T(1+x) = (1+x)^2 = 1+2x+x^2</me>,
          while
          <me> T(1) + T(x) = 1^2+x^2 = 1+x^2</me>.
          The polynomials <m>1+2x+x^2</m> are <m>1+x^2</m> not equal, and thus <m>T</m> is not linear.
        </li>
        <li>
          This question is different from the previous one. For example <m>T(1+x) = 1+x^2</m> and
          <me>T(2x+3x^3) = 2(x^2) + 3(x^2)^3 = 2x^2+3x^6</me>.
          This time it is linear:
          <me>T((f+g)(x)) = (f+g)(x^2) = f(x^2)+g(x^2)=T(f(x))+T(g(x))</me>
          <me>T(cf(x)) = (cf)(x^2) = c(f(x^2)) = cT(f(x))</me>.
        </li>
        <li>
          We have
          <me> T((f+g)(x)) = (f+g)(x-1) = f(x-1)+g(x-1) = T(f(x))+T(g(x))</me>
          and
          <me> T((cf)(x)) = (cf)(x-1) = c(f(x-1)) = cT(f(x))</me>
          and thus <m>T</m> is linear.
        </li>
        <li>
          We have
          <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 0\\0\amp 0\end{bmatrix}\right) = 1\cdot 0-0\times 0 = 0</me>
          and
          <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix}0\amp 0\\0\amp 1\end{bmatrix}\right) = 0\cdot 1-0\times 0 = 0</me>,
          but
          <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 0\\0\amp 1\end{bmatrix}\right) = 1\cdot 1-0\times 0 = 1</me>,
          so
          <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 0\\0\amp 0\end{bmatrix}\right) + T\left(\begin{bmatrix}0\amp 0\\0\amp 1\end{bmatrix}\right) \ne T\left(\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 0\\0\amp 0\end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix}0\amp 0\\0\amp 1\end{bmatrix}\right)</me>
          and thus <m>T</m> is not linear.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>V</m> be a vector space,
        and let <m>\ve{a} \neq \ve{0}</m> be a fixed vector.
        Let Define the map <m>T</m> as follows:
        <md>
          <mrow>T : V \amp \rightarrow V</mrow>
          <mrow>\ve{v} \amp  \mapsto \ve{a} + \ve{v}</mrow>
        </md>
        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              Is <m>T</m> a linear map? (Yes or no)
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Prove your assertion from (a).
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              No.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              According to <xref ref = "lin_map_zero_to_zero"/>, <m> T(0) = 0 </m> is a necessary condition for <m>T</m> to be linear. However,
              <me>
              T(\ve 0) = \ve a + 0 = \ve a \neq \ve 0.
            </me>
            Hence <m> T </m> cannot be linear.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Consider the map <m>T : \mathbb{R}^3 \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^3</m> given by <m>T\left( (x,y,z) \right) = (z,x,y)</m>.

        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              Is <m>T</m> a linear map? (Yes or no)
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Prove your assertion from (a).
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              Yes.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <md>
                <mrow> T\left((x,y,z) + (a,b,c)\right) \amp = T\left( (x+a,y+b , z + c) \right) = (z+c,x+a,y+b) </mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = (z,x,y) + (c,a,b)= T\left((x,y,z)\right) +  T\left((a,b,c)\right)
                </mrow>
              </md>
              <me>
                T(k(x,y,z)) = T(kx,ky,kz) = (kz,kx,ky) = k(z,x,y) = k T((x,y,z)).
              </me>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Define the <q>multiplication by <m>x^2</m></q> map
        <md>
          <mrow>M : \Poly_n \amp  \rightarrow \Poly_{n+2}</mrow>
          <mrow>\ve{p} \amp  \mapsto M(\ve{p})</mrow>
        </md>
        where <m>M(\ve{p})(x) = x^2 \ve{p}(x)</m>.

        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              Why does <m>M</m> map from <m>\Poly_n</m> to <m>\Poly_{n+2}</m>?
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Prove that <m>M</m> is linear.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Compute the action of <m>M</m> in the standard basis for <m>\Poly_3</m>,
              as in <xref ref="shift_example">Example</xref>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m> p(x) </m> has degree at most <m>n</m>, then <m> \ve q(x) := x^2 \ve p(x) </m> has degree at most <m>n+2</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The proof is simple and follows from the usual properties of polynomials. Using the fact that multiplication of polynomials distributes over addition we compute
              <me>
                M(\ve p + \ve q)(x) = x^2(\ve p(x) + \ve q(x)) = x^2\ve p(x) + x^2\ve q(x) = M(\ve p)(x) + M(\ve q)(x)
              </me>.
              We may consider the scalar <m> k </m> as a constant polynomial. Thus, using the commutativity and associativity of polynomial multiplication we compute
              <me>
                M(k\ve p)(x) = x^2k\ve p (x) = k(x^2 \ve p(x)) = kM(\ve p)(x).
              </me>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <md>
                <mrow>M(\ve p_0) = x^2 1 = x^2 = \ve p_2 </mrow>
                <mrow>M(\ve p_1) = x^2 x = x^3 = \ve p_3 </mrow>
                <mrow>M(\ve p_2) = x^2 x^2 = x^4 = \ve p_4 </mrow>
                <mrow>M(\ve p_3) = x^2 x^3 = x^5 = \ve p_5 </mrow>
              </md>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Define the map
        <md>
        <mrow>  C : \Poly_n \amp \rightarrow \Trig_n </mrow>
        </md>
        by the formula
        <me>
          C(p)(x) := p(\cos x).
        </me>
        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
          Compute <m>C(p)</m>, where <m>p(x)=3x^2-x+1</m>. Express your answer in terms of the standard basis for <m>Trig_2</m>,
          <me>
            T_0(x) = 1, T_1(x) = \cos x, T_2 (x) = \sin x, T_3 (x) = \cos (2x), T_4 (x) = \sin (2x)
          </me>.
        </li>
        <li>
          Is <m>C</m> a linear map?
        </li>
        <li>
          Justify that for every polynomial <m>p \in \Poly_n</m>, the function <m>C(p) \in \Trig_n</m>? (This is implicitly assumed above.)
        </li>
        <li>
          Compute <m>C(p_0), C(p_1), C(p_2), C(p_3)</m> where
          <me>
          p_0(x) = 1, p_1(x) = x, p_2(x) = x^2, p_3(x)=x^3
        </me>
        are the standard basis vectors for <m>\Poly_3</m>. Express your answers in terms of the standard basis of <m>\Trig_n</m>.
        </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        The answer to (a) is <m>C(3x^2-x+1) = 3\cos^2-\cos x+1 = \frac{3}{2}\cos (2x) - \cos(x) +\frac{5}{2}</m>.
        The answer to (b) is <q>Yes</q>.
      </p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        In each of the following you are given a linear map <m>T</m> and its value on a few specified elements. Find missing values:
      <ol label="(a)">
        <li>
          If <m>T:\Row_2\to \Row_3</m> satisfies <m>T(1,0) = (2,1,-1)</m> and <m>T(0,1) = (1,1,2)</m>, find <m>T(3,-2)</m>;
        </li>
        <li>
          If <m>T:\Row_2\to \Row_4</m> satisfies <m>T(1,1) = (1,2,3,4)</m> and <m>T(1,-1)=(3,2,1,0)</m>, find <m>T(1,0)</m> and <m>T(0,1)</m>;
        </li>
        <li>
          If <m>T:\Poly_2\to \Row_2</m>  satisfies <m>T(1+x+x^2) = (1,2)</m>, <m>T(1+x)=(2,1)</m> and <m>T(1) = (0,0)</m>, find <m>T(3+2x+x^2)</m>.
        </li>
      </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <ol label="(a)" cols="3">
          <li>
            <m>(4,1,-7)</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>(-1,0,1,2)</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>(3,3)</m>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
            We have
            <me> T(3,-2) = T(3,0)+T(0,-2) = 3T(1,0)+(-2)T(0,1) = 3(2,1,-1)-2(1,1,2) = (4,1,-7)</me>.
          </li>
          <li>
            We can say that
            <me>T(2,0) = T(1,1) + T(1,-1) = (1,2,3,4) + (3,2,1,0) = (4,4,4,4)</me>.
            Thus
            <me>T(1,0) = \frac{1}{2}(4,4,4,4) = (2,2,2,2)</me>.
            Now we can also say that
            <me> T(0,1) = T(1,1) - T(1,0) = (1,2,3,4) - (2,2,2,2) = (-1,0,1,2)</me>.
          </li>
          <li>
            This time we start by trying to write <m>3+2x+x^2</m> as a linear combination of <m>1+x+x^2</m>, <m>1+x</m> and <m>1</m>.
            Suppose that
            <me> 3+2x+x^2 = a(1+x+x^2) + b(1+x) + c(1)</me>.
            Then
            <md>
              <mrow> a+b+c \amp= 3</mrow>
              <mrow> b+c \amp = 2</mrow>
              <mrow> c \amp 1</mrow>
            </md>,
            whose solution is <m>a=b=c=1</m>.
            Thus
            <md>
              <mrow>
                T(3+2x+x^2) \amp= 1T(1+x+x^2)+1T(1+x)+1T(1)
              </mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = (1,2) + (2,1) + (0,0) </mrow>
              <mrow> \amp = (3,3)</mrow>
            </md>.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Consider the basis <m>\basis{B} = \bopen\ve{v}_1,\ve{v}_2\bclose</m> of <m>\reals^2</m>, where <m>\ve{v}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1\\0 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\ve{v}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 1\\1 \end{bmatrix}</m>, and let <m>T:\reals^2\to \reals^2</m> be the linear transformation satisfying
        <me>
          T(\ve{v}_1) = \begin{bmatrix} -1\\2 \end{bmatrix} \text{ and } T(\ve{v}_2) = \begin{bmatrix} 2\\-3 \end{bmatrix}
        </me>.
        Find a formula for <m>T\left(\begin{bmatrix}x\\y\end{bmatrix}\right)</m> and use it to find <m>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} 5\\-3 \end{bmatrix}\right)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        We have
        <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} x\\y \end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} -x+3y\\ 2x-5y\end{bmatrix}</me>
        and
        <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix}5\\-3\end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} -14\\25\end{bmatrix}</me>.
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Note that <m>\begin{bmatrix} 0\\1 \end{bmatrix} = \ve{v}_2-\ve{v}_1</m>, so
        <md>
          <mrow>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} 0\\1 \end{bmatrix}\right) \amp = T(\ve{v}_2)-T(\ve{v}_1) = \begin{bmatrix}2\\-3\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}-1\\2\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
          <mrow>
          \amp=\begin{bmatrix} 3\\ -5\end{bmatrix}
        </mrow>
      </md>.
      Now,
      <md>
        <mrow>
          T\left(\begin{bmatrix} x\\y \end{bmatrix}\right) \amp= xT\left(\begin{bmatrix} 1\\0\end{bmatrix}\right) + yT\left(\begin{bmatrix} 0\\1 \end{bmatrix}\right)</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp= x\begin{bmatrix}-1\\2 \end{bmatrix} + y\begin{bmatrix} 3\\-5 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp= \begin{bmatrix} -x+3y\\ 2x-5y\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
      </md>.
      Then
      <me> T\left(\begin{bmatrix}5\\-3\end{bmatrix}\right) = \begin{bmatrix} -14\\25\end{bmatrix}</me>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Determine the action of the gradient linear map
      <me>
        \nabla : \Poly_2[x,y] \rightarrow \Vect_1(\mathbb{R}^2)
      </me>
      from <xref ref="grad_as_linear_map"/> in terms of the standard bases
      <md>
        <mrow> \bopen q_1, q_2, q_3, q_4, q_5 \bclose  </mrow>
        <mrow> q_1 = 1, q_2 = x, q_3 = y, q_4 = x^2, q_5 = xy, q_6 = y^2</mrow>
      </md>
      of <m>\Poly_2</m> and
      <md>
        <mrow>  \bopen V_1, V_2, V_3, V_4, V_5, V_6 \bclose </mrow>
        <mrow>  V_1 = (1, 0), V_2 = (x, 0), V_3 = (y, 0) </mrow>
        <mrow> V_4 = (0, 1), V_5 = (0, x), V_6 = (0, y)</mrow>
      </md>
      of <m>\Vect_1(\mathbb{R}^2)</m>respectively.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      We first compute the values of <m>\nabla f</m>, for each polynomial <m>f</m> in the given basis for <m>\Poly_2[x,y]</m> and then write it in terms of the given basis for <m>\Vect_1(\reals^2)</m>:
      <md>
        <mrow>\nabla(1) \amp= \left(\frac{\partial 1}{\partial x},\frac{\partial 1}{\partial y}\right) = (0,0)</mrow>
        <mrow>\nabla(x) \amp= \left(\frac{\partial x}{\partial x},\frac{\partial x}{\partial y}\right) = (1,0)=V_1</mrow>
        <mrow>\nabla(y) \amp= \left(\frac{\partial y}{\partial x},\frac{\partial y}{\partial y}\right) = (0,1)=V_4</mrow>
        <mrow>\nabla(x^2) \amp= \left(\frac{\partial x^2}{\partial x},\frac{\partial x^2}{\partial y}\right) = (2x,0)=2V_2</mrow>
        <mrow>\nabla(xy) \amp= \left(\frac{\partial xy}{\partial x},\frac{\partial xy}{\partial y}\right) = (y,x)=V_3+V_5</mrow>
        <mrow>\nabla(y^2) \amp= \left(\frac{\partial y^2}{\partial x},\frac{\partial y^2}{\partial y}\right) = (0,2y)=2V_6</mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>
  </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>V</m> be the vector space of solutions to the differential equation
      <me>
        y^{(n)} + a_{n-1}(x) y^{(n-1)} + \cdots + a_1(x) y' + a_0(x) = 0
      </me>.
      Consider the <q>evaluate at <m>x=1</m></q> map
      <md>
        <mrow>T : V \amp \rightarrow \mathbb{R} </mrow>
        <mrow>y \amp \mapsto y(1)</mrow>
      </md>
      Is <m>T</m> a linear map? Prove your assertion.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      Yes. Suppose that <m>f,g</m> are two functions in <m>V</m>.
      We need to verify that
      <me>T(f+g)=(f+g)(1) = f(1)+g(1) = T(f)+T(g)</me>.
      But this is addition of functions in <m>V</m> is defined.
      Similarly, <m>T(cf) = (cf)(1) = c(f(1)) = cT(f)</m> by definition.
      Thus, <m>T</m> is linear.
    </p>
  </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Define the <q>integrate over the interval
        <m>[-1,1]</m></q> map
        <md>
          <mrow>I : \Poly_n \amp  \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</mrow>
          <mrow>\ve{p} \amp  \mapsto \int_{-1}^{1} \ve{p}(x) \, dx</mrow>
        </md>
        <ol label="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              Prove that <m>I</m> is linear.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Compute the action of <m>I</m> with respect to the standard basis <m>\ve{p}_0, \ldots, \ve{p}_3</m> for <m>\Poly_3</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Compute the action of <m>I</m> with respect to the basis
              <m>\ve{q}_0, \ldots, \ve{q}_3</m> for <m>\Poly_3</m> from <xref ref="new_basis_for_poly_3">Example</xref>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol label="(a)">

          <li>
            <p>
            We use the properties of the integral.
            <md>
              <mrow>
              I(\ve p + \ve q) \amp = \int_{-1}^1 \left( \ve p(x) + \ve q(x)\right) \, dx</mrow>
              <mrow> \amp =  \int_{-1}^1 \ve p(x) \, dx +
              \int_{-1}^1 \ve q(x) \, dx = I(\ve p) + I(\ve q)</mrow>
            </md>.
            <me>
              I(k\ve p )  = \int_{-1}^1 k\ve p(x) \, dx = k\int_{-1}^1 \ve p(x) \, dx = kI(\ve p)
            </me>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>I(\ve p_0) \amp = \int_{-1}^1 1 dx = x\rvert^1_{-1} = 2 </mrow>
              <mrow> I(\ve p_1) \amp = \int_{-1}^1 x dx = \frac{1}{2}x^2 \rvert^1_{-1} = 0</mrow>
              <mrow> I(\ve p_2) \amp = \int_{-1}^1 x^2 dx = \frac{1}{3}x^3 \rvert^1_{-1} = \frac{2}{3} </mrow>
              <mrow> I(\ve p_3) \amp = \int_{-1}^1 x^3 dx = \frac{1}{4}x^4 \rvert^1_{-1} = 0</mrow>
            </md>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              We use the results above:
              <md>
                <mrow>
                I(\ve q_0) \amp = \int_{-1}^1 1 dx = x\rvert^1_{-1} = 2</mrow>
                <mrow> I(\ve q_1) \amp = \int_{-1}^1 x dx = \frac{1}{2}x^2 \rvert^1_{-1} = 0</mrow>
                <mrow> I(\ve q_2) \amp = \int_{-1}^1 2x^2 - 1 dx = 2\int_{-1}^1 x^2 dx - \int_{-1}^1 1 =  \frac{4}{3} - 2 = -\frac{2}{3} </mrow>
                <mrow> I(\ve q_3) \amp = \int_{-1}^1 4x^3 - 3x dx = 4\int_{-1}^1 x^3 dx - 3\int_{-1}^1 x dx = 4.0 - 3.0 = 0</mrow>
              </md>.
            </p>
          </li>

        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Compute the action of the differentiation map
        <m>D : \Poly_4 \rightarrow \Poly_3</m> from <xref ref="diff_of_poly">Example</xref>
        with respect to the standard bases of these two vector spaces.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>
          D(\ve p_0) \amp = D(1) = 0  </mrow>
          <mrow> D(\ve p_1) \amp = D(x)= 1 = \ve p_0 </mrow>
          <mrow> D(\ve p_2) \amp = D(x^2) = 2x = 2\ve p_1 </mrow>
          <mrow> D(\ve p_3) \amp = D(x^3) = 3x^2 = 3\ve p_2 </mrow>
          <mrow> D(\ve p_4) \amp = D(x^4) = 4x^3 = 4 \ve p_3</mrow>
        </md>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Consider the cross-product linear map
        <m>C : \mathbb{R}^3 \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^3</m> from <xref ref="cross_prod_as_linear_map">Example</xref>
        in the case <m>\ve{w} = (1, 2, 3)</m>.
        Compute the action of <m>C</m> with respect to the standard basis of <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>C((1,0,0)) = (1,2,3) \times (1,0,0) = (0,3,-2)</mrow>
          <mrow>C((0,1,0)) = (1,2,3) \times (0,1,0) = (-3,0,1)</mrow>
          <mrow>C((0,0,1)) = (1,2,3) \times (0,0,1) = (2,-1,0)</mrow>
        </md>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>T:V\to W</m> be a linear map and suppose that <m>T(\ve{v}_1)=\ve{w}_1</m> and <m>T(\ve{v}_2)=\ve{w}_2</m>. Prove that <m>T(4\ve{v}_1-\ve{v}_2)=4\ve{w}_1-\ve{w}_2</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        We make sure to say in each step how we use the definition of a linear map:
        <md>
          <mrow> T(4\ve{v}_1-\ve{v}_2) \amp = T(4\ve{v}_1+(-1)\ve{v}_2)</mrow>
          <intertext> (this is the definition of <m>-\ve{v}_2</m>)</intertext>
          <mrow> \amp = T(4\ve{v}_1) + T((-1)\ve{v}_2)</mrow>
          <intertext> (From the first condition of a linear map)</intertext>
          <mrow> \amp = 4T(\ve{v}_1) +(-1)T(\ve{v}_2)</mrow>
          <intertext>(From the second condition of a linear map)</intertext>
          <mrow> \amp = 4(\ve{w}_1)+(-1)(\ve{w}_2)</mrow>
          <intertext>(This is how we defined <m>\ve{w}_1,\ve{w}_2</m>)</intertext>
          <mrow> \amp = 4\ve{w}_1-\ve{w}_2</mrow>
        </md>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="exercise-zero-maps-to-zero">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove that for any linear map <m>T:V \to W</m> we have <m>T(\ve{0}_V)=\ve{0}_W</m>, where <m>\ve{0}_V</m> is the zero vector in <m>V</m> and <m>\ve{0}_W</m> is the zero vector in <m>W</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>   T(\ve{0}_V) \amp = T( 0 \ve{0}_V) \amp  \text{(R8 applied to } \ve{v} = \ve{0}_V \in V)</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = 0T(\ve{0}_V) \amp  (T \text{ is linear)}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \ve{0}_W \amp  \text{(R8 applied to } \ve{v} = T(\ve{0}_V) \in W)</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>T:V \to W</m> be a linear map between two vector spaces.
        Suppose that <m>V</m> is finite-dimensional and that
        <m>\basis{B} = \bopen \ve b_1,\ldots, \ve b_n\bclose</m>
        is a basis for <m>V</m>.
        If <m>T(\ve b_i)=0</m> (the zero vector in <m>W</m>)
        for all the basis elements <m>\ve b_i</m>,
        then <m>T</m> is the zero map (i.e. it maps all vectors to <m>\ve{0}</m>).
      </p>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p>
        Any vector in <m>V</m> can be written as a linear combination of basis elements.
      </p>
    </hint>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Let <m>\ve v\in V</m> be an arbitrary vector
        Since <m>\ve b_1,\ldots, \ve b_n</m> is a basis for <m>V</m>,
        we can write <m>\ve v</m> as a linear combination
        <me>\ve v = c_1\ve b_1 + \cdots + c_n\ve b_n</me>.
        Then
        <md>
          <mrow> T(\ve v) \amp = T(c_1\ve b_1+\cdots + c_n\ve b_n) </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = T(c_1\ve b_1) + \cdots + T(c_n\ve b_n)\amp (T\text{ is linear})</mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = c_1T(\ve b_1) + \cdots + c_nT(\ve b_n)\amp (T\text{ is linear})</mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = c_1(\ve 0_W) + \cdots + c_n(\ve 0_W)\amp (\text{ each }\ve b_i\mapsto \ve 0_W)</mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = \ve 0_W + \cdots + \ve 0_W \amp(\text{R8 in }W)</mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = \ve 0_W</mrow>
        </md>.
        The choice of <m>\ve v</m> was arbitrary, which means that all vectors in <m>V</m> map to <m>\ve 0_W</m>, and thus <m>T</m> is the zero map.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>V</m> and <m>W</m> be vector spaces and <m>T:V\to W</m> a linear map.
        Show that if the vectors <m>\ve v_1,\ldots, \ve v_m</m>
        are linearly dependent in <m>V</m>,
        then the vectors <m>T(\ve v_1),\ldots, T(\ve v_m)</m> are linearly dependent in <m>W</m>.
        (Is it true that if the <m>\ve v_i</m> are linearly independent,
        then the <m>T(\ve v_i)</m> are linearly independent?)
      </p>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p>
        Whenever you need to prove that a set of vectors is linearly independent, start by assuming that there is some linear relation; and then prove that all the scalars involved are equal to 0.
      </p>
    </hint>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Suppose that there is a linear relation
        <me> \ve 0_V = c_1\ve v_1+\cdots + c_n\ve v_n</me>.
        Now we apply the linear map <m>T</m> to both sides:
        <md>
          <mrow>
            \ve 0_W \amp = T(\ve 0 _V) \amp (\text{zero maps to zero})</mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp = T(c_1\ve v_1 + \cdots + c_n\ve v_n)\amp
            (\text{from assumption above})</mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp = c_1T(\ve v_1) + \cdots + c_nT(\ve v_n)\amp
            (T\text{ is linear})</mrow>
        </md>
        The last equation is a linear relation between the vectors <m>T(\ve v_1),\ldots, T(\ve v_n)</m> in <m>W</m>.
        From our assumption that the vectors <m>T(\ve v_1),\ldots, T(\ve v_n)</m> are linearly independent in <m>W</m>, we now conclude that <m>c_1=\cdots=c_n=0</m>.
        Thus, we started with the assumption of a linear relation and proved that all the scalars involved equal 0.
        In other words, the vectors <m>\ve v_1,\ldots, \ve v_n</m> are linearly independent in <m>V</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

<exercisegroup>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Let <m>\mathcal{L}(V,\reals)</m> denote the set of all <em>linear</em> maps from <m>V</m> to <m>\reals</m>.
      We will show that this set has the natural structure of a vector space!
    </p>
    <p>
      If you have two linear maps <m>T_1:V\to \reals</m> and <m>T_2:V\to \reals</m>,
      then we can define their sum as the function that maps any
      <m>\ve v\in V</m> to <m>T_1(\ve v)+T_2(\ve v)</m>.
      Note that this is exactly the same as the addition of two functions.
    </p>
    <p>
      We can also define a scalar multiplication by defining the map
      <m>c\smul T</m> to be the map defined by <m>(c\smul T)(\ve v) = c\smul T(\ve v)</m>.
      Again, note that scalar multiplication is defined in the same way as it was for functions.
    </p>
    <p>
      So we can add any two linear maps <m>T_1,T_2</m> to get a map <m>T_1+T_2</m>
      and we can multiply any linear map <m>T</m> by a scalar to get a map <m>c\smul T</m>.
      Your first aim is to show that those maps are also linear maps.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove that if <m>V</m> is a vector space,
        then the set of all linear maps from <m>V</m> to <m>\mathbb R</m>,
        denoted <m>\mathcal L (V,\mathbb R)</m>,
        is itself a vector space.
        Since we already know that the set of all
        real valued functions from <m> V </m> to <m>\mathbb R</m> forms a vector space,
        you will only have to show that <m>\mathcal L (V,\mathbb R)</m>
        contains the function <m>\ve 0</m>, and is closed
        under both addition and scalar multiplication.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        For all <m>\ve v,\ve w \in  V</m>, for all <m>S, T \in \mathcal L (V,\mathbb R)</m> and for all <m>a , b \in \mathbb R</m>:
      <ol label="(a)">
        <li>
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>\ve 0(\ve v + \ve w) = 0 = \ve 0\ve v + \ve 0\ve w </mrow>
              <mrow>0(a\ve v) = 0 = a \ve 0 </mrow>
            </md>
            and hence <m> \ve 0 \in \mathcal L (V,\mathbb R)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>(a S)(\ve v + \ve W) = a(S (\ve v + \ve w )) = a(S \ve v+ S\ve w) = (a S)\ve v + (a S) \ve w</mrow>
              <mrow>(a S)(b \ve v) = (ab) S \ve v = b( a S \ve v) </mrow>
            </md>
            and hence <m> a S \in \mathcal L (V,\mathbb R)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>(S + T)(\ve v + \ve w) = S(\ve v+ \ve w) + T(\ve v + \ve w) </mrow>
              <mrow>= S\ve v + S \ve w + T \ve v + T \ve w  = (S + T)\ve v + (S + T)\ve w </mrow>
              <mrow>(S + T)(a \ve v) = S (a \ve v) + T(a \ve w ) = aS\ve v+  aT \ve w = a(S+T)\ve v</mrow>
            </md>
            and hence <m> S + T  \in \mathcal L (V,\mathbb R)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

      </ol>
    </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-dimension-of-dual">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>V </m> is a finite dimensional vector space, find a basis for <m> \mathcal L(V , \mathbb R) </m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Let <m>v_1,v_2,\ldots, v_n</m> be a basis for <m>V</m>.
        We claim that the following set forms a basis for <m>\mathcal L(V,\mathbb R)</m>:
        <me> T_1,\ldots, T_n</me>,
        where for any <m>i\in\{1,2,\ldots, n\}</m> we define
        <me> T_i(v_j) = \begin{cases} 1 \amp \text{if }i=j\\ 0 \amp \text{if }i\ne j \end{cases}</me>.
        (So <m>T_3(v_3) = 1</m>, but <m>T_2(v_1) = 0</m>, etc.)
        We need to check that it is linearly independent and that it spans <m> \mathcal L(V,\mathbb{R})</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        First, to prove linear independence, suppose that there is some linear relation
        <me> c_1T_1 + c_2T_2 + \cdots + c_nT_n = 0</me>.
        Here, the zero on the right, is the zero vector in <m>\mathcal{L}(V,\mathbb{R})</m>, in other words, the zero function.
        That means that if we evaluate the left hand-side at any <m>v_i</m>, we should get zero (since the right hand-side, the zero function, must evaluate to zero).
        But
        <md>
          <mrow> (c_1T_1+c_2T_2+\cdots +c_nT_n(v_i) \amp = c_1T_1(v_i) + c_2T(v_i) + \cdots + c_nT_n(v_i) </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = c_iT_i(v_i) </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = c_i </mrow>
        </md>,
        since all the terms <m>T_j(v_i)</m> with <m>i\ne j</m> are zero and <m>T_i(v_i) = 1</m>.
        This calculatation shows that the left hand-side evaluates to <m>c_i</m>, while the right hand-side must evaluate to 0.
        Thus <m>c_i=0</m>.
        But this argument applies to all <m>i</m>, so <m>c_1=c_2=\cdots = c_n=0</m>.
        This finishes the proof of linear independence.
      </p>
      <p>
        To prove that the vectors <m>T_1,\ldots, T_n</m> span <m>\mathcal{L}(V,\mathbb{R})</m>, we need to show that any linear map <m>T</m> can be written as a linear combination of them.
        By <xref ref="defining_linear_map_on_basis"/> any linear map is determined by the values of
        <me> T(v_1), T(v_2), \ldots, T(v_n)</me>.
        Since the codomain of <m>T</m> is <m>\mathbb{R}</m>, these are all real numbers.
        Let us use the symbols
        <me> d_1=T(v_1), d_2=T(v_2), \ldots, d_n=T(v_n)</me>
        for the values of <m>T</m> at each of the vectors <m>v_1,\ldots, v_n</m>.
        We then claim that
        <me> T = d_1T_1+d_2T_2 + \cdots + d_nT_n</me>.
        To show this equality of linear maps, it is enough to show that they give the same values when evaluated at <m>v_1,v_2,\ldots, v_n</m>.
        (This is another application of <xref ref="defining_linear_map_on_basis"/>.)
        But, this is verified by the computation
        <md>
          <mrow> (d_1T_1+d_2T_2+\cdots + d_nT_n)(v_i) \amp = d_1T_1(v_i) + \cdots + d_nT(v_i)</mrow>
          <mrow>  \amp = d_iT_i(v_i)</mrow>
          <mrow>  \amp = d_i </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = T(v_i)</mrow>
        </md>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Show that for every element <m>\ve v\in V</m> the map <m>\phi_{\ve v}:\mathcal{L}(V,\reals)\to \reals</m> defined by <m>\phi_{\ve v}(T)  = T(\ve v)</m> is linear.
      </p>
      <p>
        This problem is a bit harder, because it is
        something that might take long to get used to.
        You should be thinking of a linear map <m>T</m>
        as a single object that can be used as the input to this map <m>\phi_{\ve v}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Let <m>\ve T, \ve S\in \mathcal{L}(V,\mathbb{R})</m>.
        <md>
          <mrow> \varphi_{\ve v}(T+S) \amp = (T+S)(\ve v)\amp \text{Defn. of }\varphi_{\ve v}</mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = T(\ve v) + S(\ve v)\amp \text{Defn. of }T+S</mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = \varphi_{\ve v}(T) + \varphi_{\ve v}(S)</mrow>
        </md>.
        Similarly
        <md>
          <mrow> \varphi_{\ve v}(cT) \amp = (cT)(\ve v)</mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = c\cdot T(\ve v)</mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = c\varphi_{\ve v}(T)</mrow>
        </md>,
        so <m>\varphi_{\ve v}</m> is linear.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <title> Challenge!</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Again, let <m>V</m> be a vector space.
        Let <m>W</m> be the vector space <m>\mathcal{L}(V,\reals)</m>.
        So its elements are linear maps from <m>V</m> to <m>\reals</m>.
        Now consider the map <m>\Phi:V \to \mathcal{L}(W,\reals)</m>
        defined by <m>\Phi(\ve v) = \phi_{\ve v}</m>.
        (Recall from the previous problem that <m>\phi_{\ve v}</m>
        is a linear map from <m>\mathcal{L}(V,\reals)</m>
        to <m>\reals</m>, so it really does belong to <m>\mathcal{L}(W,\reals)</m>,
        so the definition of <m>\Phi</m> makes sense.)
        Prove that <m>\Phi</m> is also a linear map.
      </p>
      <p>
        Bonus: If <m>V</m> is finite-dimensional, prove that <m>\Phi</m> is an isomorphism (<xref ref="def-isomorphism" />).
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        We need to show that <m>\Phi(\ve v+\ve w) = \Phi(\ve v) + \Phi(\ve w)</m>, in other words that <m>\varphi_{\ve v + \ve w} = \varphi_{\ve v} + \varphi_{\ve w}</m>.
        Since both of these are functions, we show that they are equal, by showing that wherever we evaluate them, we get the same answer.
        Let <m>T\in W</m> be arbitrary.
        Then
        <md>
          <mrow> \varphi_{\ve v+\ve w}(T) \amp = T(\ve v+\ve w)</mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = T(\ve v) + T(\ve w)\amp T\text{ is linear}</mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = \varphi_{\ve v}(T) + \varphi_{\ve w}(T)</mrow>
        </md>.
        A similar computation can be done to show that <m>\varphi_{c\ve v} = c\varphi_{\ve v}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        To show that <m>\Phi</m> is an isomorphism, we show that <m>\Dim \mathcal{L}(W,\mathbb{R}) = \Dim V</m> and that <m>\Phi</m> is injective (see <xref ref="Ch3Sec6InjectiveSurjective" />).
        By applying <xref ref="ex-dimension-of-dual"/> to <m>V</m> we have <m>\Dim W = \Dim V</m> and by applying it to <m>W</m> we have <m>\Dim \mathcal{L}(W,\mathbb{R}) = \Dim W</m>, which proved our first point.
        To show that <m>\Phi</m> is injective, assume that <m>\Phi(\ve v)</m> is the zero function on <m>W</m> for some <m>\ve v\in V</m>.
        This means that for any linear map <m>T</m>, we have <m>\varphi_{\ve v} = T(\ve v) = 0</m>.
        But if <m>V</m> is not the zero vector space, we can always define at least one linear map that is not zero at <m>\ve v</m>.
        This is because, we can choose some basis for <m>V</m> that has <m>\ve v</m> as one of its elements and define <m>T</m> by specifying its values on this basis, making sure that <m>T(\ve v) \ne 0</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

</exercisegroup>

</exercises>

